  abstract      = {The article analyzes biopolitical violence in the Andean foothills of the Los Ríos region in southern Chile, as well as the resistance practices of rural and Mapuche communities in the face of private property understood as the organizing axis of life. Drawing on an interdisciplinary approach and ethnographic fieldwork, it examines territorial dispossession, criminalization, and the exercise of violence by corporate actors who manage and sustain precarity. The analysis of collective memories and territorial recovery processes, through an intersectional lens, contributes to understanding the emerging conflicts and the strategies of agency deployed by the communities.},
