  title         = {Haitian Migration, Job Segregation and Racism in Santiago, Chile (2016-2023)},
  year          = {2025},
  journal       = {CONVERGENCIA-REVISTA DE CIENCIAS SOCIALES},
  abstract      = {The objective of the article is to analyze the segregated workspaces and racism experienced by Haitian people in Santiago, Chile. The research employs a qualitative method, based on ethnographic observation and in-depth interviews. The results indicate that in the wholesale markets, commonly known as Vegas, the Haitian community is employed as sales assistants, cleaners, and loaders, while in construction companies, they work as day laborers. They face excessive working hours and racial discrimination due to issues of “color”, class, and nationality. The study concludes that upon arriving in Santiago, Haitian migrants are placed in segregated workspaces, where their professional qualifications and work experience from their countries of origin are delegitimized, while Chileans are racially positioned as superior and enjoy better working conditions, despite often lacking higher qualifications.},
